Redesign the entire Protocol Builder interface to improve navigation clarity,
reduce cognitive load, standardize visual hierarchy, and fully optimize
both laptop and mobile experiences.

The objective is to transform the interface into a predictable,
clinically-oriented workflow system with strong usability,
consistent behavior, and mobile-first architecture.

This redesign must preserve existing clinical logic,
but restructure navigation, layout, visual hierarchy,
and interaction models.

==================================================
GLOBAL OBJECTIVES
==================================================

Improve:

• Navigation clarity
• Cognitive load reduction
• Visual consistency
• Action discoverability
• Clinical readability
• Mobile usability
• Timeline comprehension
• Safety workflow usability

The interface must feel:

• Clinical
• Predictable
• Efficient
• Safe
• Professional

Avoid decorative complexity.

Prioritize functional clarity.

==================================================
SECTION 1 — STANDARDIZE WORKFLOW NAVIGATION
==================================================

Current issue:

Navigation exists in multiple parallel systems:

• Top step bar
• Sidebar
• Buttons inside pages

This creates ambiguity.

--------------------------------------------------

Required changes:

1. Make top step bar the PRIMARY navigation.

2. Convert sidebar into SECONDARY contextual navigation.

3. Allow sidebar fields to be clickable.

When clicking a sidebar field:

• Scroll to related section
• Highlight field
• Do not reload page

Use smooth scrolling.

Add temporary highlight animation.

--------------------------------------------------

Result:

Sidebar becomes:

Navigation Map
Not just information display.

